Nvidia in 2022 - PCIE power is obsolete, we are moving to a new power connector called 12VHPWR
Nvidia in 2025 - 12VHPWR isn't necessary for low end GPU's anymore, PCIE is fine shuv that back in to save costs.

aka - that 12VHPWR was such an absolute dumpster fire of a connector that Nvidia just gave up on it for GPU's that consume under 200W just to save their asses from more "GPU in flames" lawsuits...

tbh, i still don't quite understand what was the point of 12VHPWR to begin with?
the PCIE X8 power connector is capable of carrying up to 300W of power, and the motherboard PCIE connector is capable of carrying up to 75W of power (i believe modern motherboards and chipsets actually are now capable of carrying up to 150W on that PCIE Slot, and Asus's BTF motherboard can actually supply up to 650W from the PCIE slot + BTF connector)
so basically speaking, instead of introducing a new untested standard (that keeps frying GPU's for the past 3 years) Nvidia could've just specced their high power consumption cards with two 8 pin PCIE power connectors - and the PCIE Power standard should've just been updated to officially support up to 300W of power draw per 8 pin connector (the standard specs its a 250W connector but because it is such an overbuilt standard in reality it would actually support carrying 300W just fine)

i'd rather have had a RTX4090 or RTX5090 with two 8-Pin PCIE Power cables, heck even three 8-Pin PCIE power cables and have them not burst in flames, than have a single shitty small connector that has to be plugged in JUST RIGHT to not cause your power supply or 2000-4000$ GPU to burst into flames.

The 5070 has a 192 bit bus, its faster, but limits it in 6 Gb increments, so 6 Gb or 12 Gb or 18 gb Vram available.
